          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"week_number\":1,\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weekly_target_km\":55,\"is_deload_week\":false,\"sunday\":{\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"notes\":\"26 km at easy pace (5:08–5:53/km). This anchors your week and builds the aerobic foundation you'll need for marathon distance. Keep it conversational — you should be able to speak in full sentences throughout.\"},\"monday\":{\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Full rest or light walking. You've just come off a solid long run; let the adaptation begin. Recovery is where fitness is actually built.\"},\"tuesday\":{\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"notes\":\"12 km easy (5:08–5:53/km). Shake out the legs from Sunday. This is genuinely easy — not 'comfortably hard.' If in doubt, slow down.\"},\"wednesday\":{\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Rest day. Four-day weeks mean your non-run days carry real recovery value. Use this space intentionally.\"},\"thursday\":{\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"notes\":\"10 km total: 2 km easy warm-up, 5 km at threshold pace (4:16/km), 3 km easy cool-down. This is your first quality session — threshold work trains your body to sustain marathon-relevant effort by raising your lactate threshold.\"},\"friday\":{\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Rest day. A buffer before Saturday's second quality run means you arrive fresh and able to hit the paces.\"},\"saturday\":{\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"notes\":\"7 km easy (5:08–5:53/km). A short, relaxed aerobic top-up to round out the week. Keep HR low and effort minimal.\"},\"week_summary\":\"Welcome to Week 1, Priya. Given your most recent full week was 52 km, we're starting at 55 km — a modest, confident step that respects your training history without overcooking the opening week. Your pace-zone index of 49.7 places you squarely in advanced territory, and the 3:15 marathon goal (4:37/km race pace) is genuinely within reach given your half-marathon fitness. This week's structure establishes the rhythm we'll build from: long run on Sunday, a midweek threshold session to start touching race-relevant effort, and easy running to fill out the aerobic base. Everything is capped at 90 minutes per your preference, and all sessions are flexible for after 7 AM. The key this week is restraint — especially on Tuesday and Saturday. Easy really does mean easy here.\"}"
        }
      ]
    }
